player.seasonOutlook: Davis was arguably the top producer in the league last season before his trade request to the Lakers was made public and his season subsequently went downhill. He is 26 years old, in the midst of what should be his peak seasons, and he will be playing next to one of the elite players and playmakers in the NBA in LeBron James. Davis should face less defensive attention and be put in better positions to score, improving his percentages with only James capping his volume upside.

Leonard turned the basketball world upside down this offseason when he joined the Clippers and brought Paul George with him. He missed 22 games last season for maintenance purposes, and with the Clippers boasting deep talent and George as well, Leonard could still get plenty of rest again this season. He should have excellent per-game stats, if a bit attenuated due to his strong teammates, but the maintenance games could drop him slightly in the rankings.

Walker replaces Kyrie Irving as the high-volume lead guard on the Celtics but presumably will take a step back usage-wise with his stronger supporting cast in Boston. His scoring and 3-point volume likely decrease, but his efficiency and assists could potentially take upticks in his new role.

Russell established himself as an NBA All-Star with the Nets last season, and now makes the big transition to more of an off-ball role with the Warriors this season. Russell will become at best a tertiary offensive creator behind Stephen Curry and Draymond Green, but he will play most of the season in the Klay Thompson (ACL) role which should produce lots of 3-pointers and scoring opportunities for a Warriors squad that will need the points.

Love missed 60 games last season and 105 games during the past three seasons as injuries have taken a major toll. The Cavaliers are in full rebuild mode, which doesn't seem to fit with a 30-something All-Star like Love. If he remains with the team and healthy, Love still has 20-10 upside with strong 3-point volume from a big man.

Bledsoe is established in his role as the third scorer and secondary playmaker for the Bucks, and if his free throw percentage bounces back into the 80% range after an eight-year low of 75% last season, Bledsoe would be a strong across-the-board contributor with very little downside this season.

Gallinari missed only 14 games last season, the fewest he's missed since the 2011-12 season. He also turned in career highs with 19.8 PPG, 6.1 RPG, 2.4 3PG and 46.3 FG%. This offseason, he moved from a deep Clippers squad to a depleted Thunder team, where he projects as the featured scorer. He could put up top-30 value in fantasy drafts, but the specter of injury likely slides him into the early-middle rounds.

Jordan is exactly who he is at this point of his career, with per-possession averages that have stayed rock steady over the past five seasons, whether he was playing with the Clippers, Mavericks or Knicks. We thus know what to expect from him per minute in Brooklyn, with the only question being how the minutes are split between Jordan and Jarrett Allen. His ceiling is a bit lower due to the time split, although there were wild rumors that he and Allen were working on 3-point shots during the offseason in hopes of playing together.

Richardson is coming off the best season of his career, during which he set  personal records across the board as "the man" for the Heat. This season, he will play more of a secondary role for the 76ers, which caps his scoring and assist volume but could lead to better shooting percentages, more 3-pointers and better defensive stats. That might make him more valuable in roto than points leagues.

Winslow expanded his game last season when he started for extended periods at point guard, a skill set that could make him valuable as a secondary ball handler and defensive forward while playing off of Jimmy Butler. Winslow projects as a solid all-around threat with more than a 3-pointer and steal per game.

Isaac was drafted sixth overall in 2017 as an athletic development prospect, and last season, he continued to develop and started 64 games. This season, he projects as a double-digit scorer with solid rebounding and could average more than one block, steal and 3-pointer per game. This gives him expected value near the top 100 of roto leagues with upside to flirt with the top 50 if he makes a significant, but achievable, third-year jump.

Thomas finished top-5 in the NBA MVP race just three seasons ago, but he was essentially out of the league last season as he continued to recover from hip surgery. This campaign, he will battle Ish Smith for minutes at the Wizards� point with John Wall out. If healthy, Thomas has the opportunity to win the job, though he currently projects as the backup. Health is by far the biggest question mark with him this season and moving forward.
Currently unsigned, but REALLY wishes that he were signed.

Tucker embraced a larger role for the Rockets last season, playing 34.2 MPG in 82 games. His noteworthy contributions were reflected in 1.8 3PG and 1.6 SPG, with 5.8 RPG as a third category of interest. He is a real-life defensive specialist, so he is unlikely to produce the volume to be valuable in points leagues, but that unique combo of steals and 3-pointers could generate some interest late in roto drafts.

Harden will be welcoming old teammate Russell Westbrook to town, and both have claimed a willingness to sacrifice personal stats for a championship. The best mix may be Westbrook playing more on-ball, which would lead to a small decrease in scoring and assists but perhaps an uptick in 3-pointers and shooting percentage for the new-look Rockets.

Vucevic is coming off a career-best season, during which he set personal bests with 20.8 PPG, 12.0 RPG, 1.1 BPG and 1.1 3PG. He had struggled with health in previous seasons, but he was also able to turn in a career-high 80 games last season. While it should be noted that this effort came in a contract year, Vucevic has the talent to build upon that success this season if he can remain healthy again -- a big 'if.'

Holiday is the primary perimeter threat on the young, rebuilding Pelicans, and the head coach has already called this Holiday's team to lead. Rookie Zion Williamson should have high usage, but not as high as the recently departed Anthony Davis, so Holiday should have upside to actually improve on his volume numbers this season.

Aldridge settled in as option 1B on offense next to DeMar DeRozan last season, averaging 21.3 PPG on 51.9% from the field while turning in the best rebounding and defensive numbers of his Spurs career. He projects to similar numbers this season, as the Spurs have improved their backcourt but still will rely on Aldridge to carry the load up front.

Green is expected to be more productive this season with Kevin Durant gone, likely taking on even more of a ballhandling/distributing role than usual for the Warriors. He is one of a handful of players who has the upside to flirt with averaging a triple-double this season.

Adebayo projects as the starting center for the Heat this season with Hassan Whiteside out of town, though he still has some competition for minutes in Kelly Olynyk and newly acquired Meyers Leonard. Adebayo has low double-double potential with a steal and a block per game; numbers that could allow him to flirt with a top-150 ranking if he earns a large enough minutes share.

Paul was traded from the Rockets to the Thunder, which gives him very nice upside as "the man" on his new team as opposed to having to play subordinate to James Harden's huge usage. Paul still has the potential to put up big numbers, but injuries have robbed him of 69 games during the past three seasons, which makes health a huge question mark entering his age-34 season.

Covington was traded to the Timberwolves early last season and put up the best scoring numbers of his career for 22 games before having his season end early because of injury. This season he projects for more of the same, mixing volume 3-point shooting with excellent defensive numbers and solid contributions across the board.

Rubio moved to the Suns this offseason, giving them the point guard they've desperately needed for the past couple of seasons. The offense will still run through Devin Booker, but Rubio should have good assist potential on a team with several strong finishers, and he should get open 3-pointers as the defense will not be focused on him at all.

Bridges is a young high flyer who spent his rookie season trying to develop enough of a jumper to be a strong 3-and-D role player, but with all of the offseason losses the Hornets have sustained, there's a case to be made that Bridges is now the most talented player on the team. If he starts at power forward, he has double-digit scoring upside with solid rebounding and possibly a 3-pointer, a block and a steal per game on average.

Lopez has found a late-career renaissance as a stretch-5 playing off of the defensive attention demanded by Giannis Antetokounmpo. Lopez notched career highs with 2.3 3PG and 2.2 BPG last season, and he appears set to reprise the same role with similar production this season.

Herro has generated some buzz as a rookie with upside on the youth-strapped Heat. The Heat have depth on the perimeter, so Herro might have to earn his way onto the court, but he has a shooter-scorer skill set that is unique on the Heat and could allow him to end the season as a double-digit scorer with plus 3-point contributions if he gets the minutes.

Robinson had an excellent rookie season, rising from a second-round draft pick to the starting center on the Knicks to end the season. Robinson averaged 12.0 PPG, 11.6 RPG, 2.5 BPG and 1.1 SPG in 32.2 MPG during the last eight games of the season, and enters this season as the presumptive starter for the Knicks. While the team has a plethora of free-agent big men, they are all power forwards and most contribute primarily on offense. Robinson is an athletic, defense-minded center with the explosiveness to put up top-50 production if he continues to get starter minutes this season.

Huerter started his rookie season slowly, then dealt with injury during the second half of the season. However, he had a month stretch from Dec. 12 through Jan. 19 when he gave an indication of what he could do as a healthy, full-time starter with averages of 13.4 PPG, 3.2 APG, 3.1 RPG and 2.4 3PG on 42.7 FG% and 39.6 3FG%. Coming into his second season, this is what he will be looking to build upon.

Satoransky has backed up John Wall for the Wizards during the past couple of seasons, and proved that he could produce starting-caliber fantasy numbers when called upon to start in Wall's absence. This season, he joins the Bulls, but his potential is capped by the presence of Kris Dunn and lottery rookie Coby White on the roster. He has some upside but could also end up getting squeezed out of opportunities if everyone is healthy.

Towns became a different player last season after Jimmy Butler was traded, then stepped up again around the new year to average 27.2 PPG, 13.0 RPG, 3.9 APG, 1.9 3PG and 1.6 BPG during the last 43 games of the season after a very slow start. The Timberwolves are back to being Towns' team and he's approaching his athletic peak, which should translate into a career-best season for the Big KAT.

Irving fits almost perfectly into the possession-usage absence left by the departing D'Angelo Russell. Last season, Russell averaged 18.7 FGA and 7.0 APG, while Irving averaged 18.5 FGA and 6.9 APG. Irving is the better, more efficient shooter, including from downtown, and he should maintain that on his new Nets squad with per-possession averages and minutes similar to what he has shown the past several seasons, especially with Kevin Durant expected to miss most or all of the season.

Griffin settled into his role as the primary offensive option for the Pistons last season, setting new career highs of 24.5 PPG and 2.5 3PG to go with solid numbers across the board. He also had his healthiest season since 2013-14, playing in 75 games. Health permitting, Griffin should continue to produce at a similar level this season as his primary supporting cast members stayed consistent.

Booker has improved tangibly in each of his four seasons thus far and is coming off a career-best season in which he averaged significant career highs with 26.6 PPG and 6.8 APG while shooting 46.7% from the floor. The Suns are entirely his team now, plus Deandre Ayton is drawing more attention inside, which should only open things up for Booker to thrive this season.

Middleton is clearly established as the second "star" on the Bucks, coming off his first All-Star selection and having earned a big contract this offseason. He is a strong perimeter scorer with a sneaky-strong all-around game who gets to bomb away for a lot of open 3-pointers because of the defensive attention that teammate Giannis Antetokounmpo draws.

Conley was traded to the Jazz this summer, which caps his scoring volume compared to his time in Memphis, but it might improve his assist and field goal percentage upside by playing with more talented teammates. His biggest concern is health, as he has missed double-figure games in five straight seasons, including the 70 games that he missed because of injury in the 2017-18 season.

LeVert began last season like a budding All-Star, averaging 20.3 PPG on 48.9 FG% with 4.4 RPG, 4.0 APG, 1.6 3PG and 1.4 SPG during his first 12 starts before suffering a foot injury that shelved him until February and robbed him of his explosiveness for the rest of the season. He bounced back to average 21 PPG on 49.3% FG in the playoffs, which helped earn him a big extension this offseason and likely the opportunity to build on that production as the starting small forward alongside new point guard Kyrie Irving this season.

Carter was in the midst of a promising rookie campaign when his season was cut short by injury. Playing 25.2 MPG, Carter was averaging 19.9 points, 13.4 rebounds, 3.4 assists, 2.5 blocks and 1.1 steals per 100 possessions. This season, Carter should get closer to starter minutes on a young, rebuilding Bulls team and has double-double potential with strong defensive stats and good percentages.

Ingram was traded in the package for Anthony Davis, and slots in as the starting small forward for the Pelicans this season. However, he is likely the third scoring option, at best, behind Jrue Holiday and Zion Williamson, and he won't get to handle the ball much on a team featuring Lonzo Ball and Holiday. Ingram's peripheral stats aren't enough to make him an impact player if his scoring declines, limiting his upside even if he's able to return to full health after the blood clot issues that ended last season for him.

Barnes saw his scoring volume limited after his trade to the Kings last season, and he could see that continue this season as the Kings look to further develop their young talents. Barnes doesn't have a versatile enough game to remain of interest in points leagues if his scoring slides, but he averaged a couple of 3-pointers per game last season, and that could keep him on the radar in roto leagues.

Prince's development stagnated a bit in his third season, partially because of the injuries that caused him to miss 27 games. He started 129 of the 137 games that he played for the Hawks during the past two seasons and projects as a likely starter as a stretch-4 for the Nets, a role that could lead to slightly more 3-point opportunities but fewer rebounds due to their two huge centers.

Oladipo established himself as an All-Star with the Pacers before he tore his ACL midway through last season. His return date is murky, but the consensus is that he should be ready to go sometime around the New Year. The team has spoken of limiting his workload upon return, and has added perimeter scorers Malcolm Brogdon, Jeremy Lamb and T.J. Warren during the offseason, which should take some offensive pressure off of Oladipo moving forward.

Fultz is one of the biggest enigma's in the NBA. He was the consensus No. 1 overall pick in the draft just two years ago, but a mysterious shoulder injury and wildly inconsistent shooting mechanics got him traded from the 76ers to the Magic for role players last season. If Fultz can heal and find his shot and confidence, which might be easier in a smaller market like Orlando, he still has the hidden potential to develop into the talented lead guard that he was drafted to be. But he also has the potential to turn in another lost season, making him a high-risk/high-reward late-round flier candidate in fantasy drafts.

Smith was the centerpiece of the trade that sent Kristaps Porzingis to the Mavericks last season, and he enters this season as the presumptive point guard of the future for the Knicks. Smith had a promising rookie season when healthy but regressed as a sophomore and battled injuries that cost him 29 games. If healthy, Smith projects as a plus scorer who could contribute in assists, 3-pointers and steals, but he could be a drag on both shooting percentage categories.

Simmons improved as a sophomore, once again flirting with averaging a triple-double, but he is still infamous for his lack of any sort of a jump shot. He shot 56.3% from the field almost entirely from close-range, but there is increased push for Simmons to develop a jumper to take his team to the next level. If he adds a jumper, he'd become nigh unguardable -- but for now, he projects similarly to last season, although with moderate improvements across the board.

Siakam stepped up in his third season, averaging 16.9 PPG, 6.9 RPG, 3.1 APG and 1.0 3PG while shooting an efficient 54.9 FG% and 78.5 FT% to win the NBA Most Improved Player award. Siakam has the upside to pop again this season as the presumptive best player on the Raptors, moving into the role left empty by the departure of Kawhi Leonard. Siakam projects as a top-25 player in both roto and points leagues.

Mitchell improved his scoring volume as a sophomore, but his scoring efficiency actually regressed slightly. However, the addition of Mike Conley Jr. to the backcourt should make Mitchell's life easier and put him in better position to score. He could be in for a Year 3 leap that could catapult him to among the top-scoring perimeter threats in the NBA this season.

Capela has improved every season of his career and has made himself into an impact big man on offense as part of the deadly Rockets pick-and-roll game. Swapping Chris Paul for Russell Westbrook shouldn't hurt him, as Westbrook cultivated Steven Adams in a similar role in his last stop. Capela's rebounding, high-efficiency scoring and defense give him top-25 upside in points leagues this season.

Kuzma appears set to start the season as a sixth man who should produce like a starter, similar to a Lou Williams role in the frontcourt. Kuzma is the third primary scorer for the Lakers behind LeBron James and Anthony Davis, will be the first option on the second unit and the stretch-4 on the closing unit. He had an impressive rookie season, improved in his second season and should flirt with a 20-PPG season and a potential run at NBA Sixth Man of the Year.

Favors has been relatively healthy during the past two seasons and settled in as a high-efficiency double-double threat with strong defensive numbers despite playing only about 25 MPG next to and behind Rudy Gobert. This season, he joins the Pelicans and projects as their starting center. If this role comes with starter minutes, he could improve his counting stats enough to warrant a mid-round pick in fantasy drafts.

Barrett was considered the top high school player in America going into last season, and he turned in an excellent campaign at Duke to solidify his pedigree. He has a chance to be one of the leading scorers on the Knicks, and his playmaking skill should give him well-rounded offensive stats. He is worthy of consideration once you get to the middle rounds of fantasy drafts due to his upside, and if he's available later he could be a steal.

Wiggins turned in the worst scoring effort of his career last season, his second straight down campaign after turning in a career-best season in 2016-17, but he enters this season with no Jimmy Butler and a new max extension that ensures he remains a primary scoring option for the Timberwolves this season. If he can improve on last season's career-best 1.6 3-pointers per game and get back up in the area of the 23.6 PPG he averaged in 2016-17, his fantasy value could bounce back towards positive this season.

Teague had a solid per-game effort last season but struggled with consistent injuries that left him with a career-low 42 games played after averaging more than 74 games played during his first nine seasons. If he can return to health, Teague still has a role as the primary lead guard and perimeter playmaker for the Timberwolves that could result in a top-100 fantasy season in 2019-20.

Allen had a breakout sophomore season, becoming one of the most spectacular shot-blockers in the NBA. He was poised to slot in as an impact fantasy big man this season until the Nets signed former two-time All-NBA center DeAndre Jordan to a four-year deal. Both big men are strong interior forces with no history of shooting touch, though both claim to be working on their 3-point skills in hopes of playing together. This development puts a cap on Allen's upside, though his per-minute numbers have been consistent as a pro.

Millsap turned in his lowest scoring volume since 2008-09 but his best field goal percentage since 2011-12 last season, a trend that probably continues this season on a very talented Nuggets roster. Millsap remains a strong source of rebounding, defensive categories and 3-pointers that make him slightly more valuable in roto leagues than points leagues for this season.

Dragic was limited to only 36 games last season due to recurring knee issues that resulted in arthroscopic surgery and a long in-season recovery that compressed his numbers all season. If healthy, Dragic has some bounce-back potential this season, though the presence of Jimmy Butler limits his usage and volume upside, while potentially helping with his scoring efficiency.

Barton battled injury all last season, which resulted in his worst season numbers as a member of the Nuggets. Barton has Sixth Man of the Year upside and can average mid-teens with solid rebounds, 3-pointers and even assists if he gets close to the 30 MPG that he has averaged during the past four seasons.

Brooks had a strong rookie season, but health was a problem as a sophomore, when he was limited to only 18 games. He has the potential to start on the wing for the rebuilding Grizzlies this season, which would give him solid upside to be a double-digit scorer with more than a 3-pointer and a steal per game.

Hart regressed in his second season after a promising rookie campaign and an MVP award at the 2018 NBA summer league, struggling with injuries and his shot as the sixth man for the Lakers. This season, his skill level probably bounces back, but his new team has so much quality depth at the guard positions that Hart could struggle to get enough minutes for fantasy relevance. He probably will go undrafted in most fantasy leagues but watch him because if he gets sixth-man minutes, he has the upside to be a strong source of 3-pointers with solid scoring and steal numbers.

Antetokounmpo has improved in every season as a pro, culminating with his first MVP trophy last season. He is still only 24 and just approaching his athletic peak. With all of the emphasis and extra work he's been putting into shooting, he may add a reasonable 3-point shot to his already MVP-caliber repertoire this season.

Drummond is the best rebounder in the NBA, having led the league in rebounding in three of the past four seasons. He is also coming off a career-high scoring effort at 17.3 PPG, and his mixture of volume and efficiency make him a top-20 prospect in points leagues, although his free throw percentage hurts him in roto.

Collins took a big step up in his second season and seems poised to do that again in his third. He flirted strongly with being a 20-10 big man last season while shooting 56% from the field, and with health and another offseason of improvement, he could have a magical season as a borderline elite prospect.

Hield blossomed into a true impact player in his third season, averaging career bests of 20.7 PPG, 5.0 RPG, 2.5 APG and 3.4 3PG. He will play a similar role for what may be a more talented Kings squad this season and should continue to get good looks that could allow him to improve again. He projects to a top-30 player in roto leagues and top-50 in points leagues.

Murray is coming off a career season, and he very well might make a similar leap this campaign. He is the unquestioned lead guard and perimeter scorer for a strong Nuggets offense, and he also made strides as a playmaker, which gives him the upside of 20-5-5 with two treys and a steal this season.

Sabonis is expected to start at power forward this season, theoretically ending the minutes battle between he and center Myles Turner. This could create spacing issues, but Turner has 3-point range and Sabonis is the better rebounder with better interior offensive skills, so it could potentially work. With more minutes, Sabonis could be in for a bit of a leap as a nightly double-double with mid-teens scoring and even quality assists from the frontcourt.

Lowry is coming off his lowest scoring average since 2010-11 last season, but with Kawhi Leonard gone, Lowry might be asked to carry a larger offensive role this season. Age and health are concerns for Lowry, as he will turn 34 during the season and has missed at least 17 games in two of his past three seasons. If healthy, he has the upside to approach the 18.9 PPG that he averaged during the 2016-17 and 2017-18 seasons combined with the 8.7 APG that he turned in last season.

Horford joined the 76ers as a free agent this summer, and projects to shuffle between power forward and center to get his minutes. He likely becomes the fifth option on offense, which impacts both his scoring upside and his quietly valuable assist potential. He should still be a good source of defensive stats and 3-pointers from the center position, and his scoring efficiency could improve, but his volume is capped by the move.

Lamb parlayed a career-best scoring effort in Charlotte last season into a new gig with the Pacers, and he is expected to start on the wing as a primary scorer until Victor Oladipo is able to return. He figures to get the minutes and the shots to build upon his strong play from last season, but he might get better looks with the Pacers having more talent than he played with before.

Nance flirted with a low double-double in 67 games with the Cavaliers last season and has the upside to actually reach those numbers this season if he earns starter minutes. He is battling Tristan Thompson for action, but he is younger and has more upside on a rebuilding team, which should seemingly afford him more opportunity.

Harris turned in a career-best effort last season, but per possession he was almost the exact same player in 2018-19 as he was the season before, he just played more minutes. He settled in as the full-time starter on the wing, a role he seems likely to reprise for the new-look Nets. Harris shot a career- and NBA-best 47.4% from long range last season and is at 42.7% for his career, so he should continue to be a marksman this season.

VanVleet improved to produce fantasy-worthy numbers off the bench last season, including 11.0 PPG, 4.8 APG, 2.6 RPG and 1.8 3PG in 27.5 MPG. With starting point guard Kyle Lowry getting older and more injury brittle, VanVleet has upside to improve on this production this season. He is a mid-to-late-round prospect in fantasy drafts.

Saric was traded to the Suns this offseason, a move that could pay big dividends if he secures the starting power forward role as expected. Still only 25 years old, Saric is only two seasons removed from flashing 20-10 upside for extended stretches with the 76ers. Saric fits well as a stretch-4 next to Deandre Ayton and could be poised for a breakout season.

Cauley-Stein stagnated a bit with the Kings last season but gets a new opportunity in a unique setting with the Warriors this season. Cauley-Stein will be asked to rebound and protect the rim, but the Warriors might actually need some of his scoring potential this season with Kevin Durant gone and Klay Thompson replaced by D'Angelo Russell. Cauley-Stein averaged 11.9 PPG with 55.6% shooting from the field last season, and he could improve both of those numbers slightly with the Warriors this season while flirting with a double-double every night.

Porter averaged 17.5 PPG on 48.3 FG% with 5.5 RPG and 2.6 3PG during his 15 games with the Bulls last season, indicating that his current role could allow him to be a more effective scoring version of the otherwise all-around statistical garbage man that he had always shown himself to be with the Wizards.

Howard missed almost the entirety of last season with a back injury and off-the-court issues, but he returns this season for a second stint with the Lakers. His first went poorly during the 2012-13 season, but this time Howard will be playing more of a defensive/finisher role next to LeBron James and Anthony Davis. His volume is therefore capped, though he still has low double-double upside.

Coming off the first significant injury in the 16th season of his career, playing next to arguably the most talented teammate of his career in Anthony Davis, James should be expected to cut back a bit in minutes and scoring to stay fresh through the season for an attempt at a championship run. His numbers should remain similar to usual, with perhaps small steps back across the board in volume but elevated efficiency.

Gobert is coming off his best season, during which he set  career highs with 15.9 PPG, 12.9 RPG, 2.0 APG and 0.8 SPG. He remains one of the best shot-blockers in the league with 2.3 BPG last season, and his 66.9% shooting from the field led the NBA. In a points league, he projects to challenge for a top-15 spot in the rankings and his blocks give him a big boost in roto formats.

Fox exploded as a sophomore, improving significantly across the board from his rookie season. This season, Fox's upside could push 20 points and 10 dimes with solid rebounds and steals and a serviceable 3-point shot. Free throw shooting is his one rotisserie weak spot.

Valanciunas has been one of the best per-minute producers in the NBA for several seasons, but his minutes were capped while he was with the Raptors. Last season he was traded to the Grizzlies and given more playing time. He responded with impact volume numbers that, if maintained for the entire season with good health, would make him an easy top-50 performer.

Brogdon turned in the best numbers of his young career last season, and parlayed that into a big offseason deal to become the lead guard for the Pacers. He has the potential to put up big volume stats while Victor Oladipo is out and should fit well next to him up on his return. Brogdon also is a strong source of scoring, 3-pointers and percentages with solid boards from the guard position and possibly steals as well.

Morant projects as one of the biggest impact rookies in this class, with the keys to the Grizzlies as the starting point guard from Day 1. He should be among the rookie leaders in points, assists, steals and possibly 3-pointers, though his scoring efficiency and turnovers could be negative. He has clear top-100 upside conservatively, and could push for top-75.

Warren struggled with injuries that limited him to only 43 games last season with the Suns, and in the offseason, he was traded to a Pacers team that lost Thaddeus Young to free agency and will be without leading scorer Victor Oladipo to start the season. Warren is a professional scorer who added a deadly 3-point shot to his arsenal last season and has 20 PPG upside with solid peripherals if he gets starter minutes for the Pacers.

Parker was signed to a backup role behind budding star John Collins. The Hawks have young talent on the wing, but Parker could carve out an instant-offense role off the bench and even get some time next to Collins in some small-ball lineups. He's a natural scorer, but without the minutes to volume score, he doesn't provide much else. He's also a huge injury risk, making him more of a free agent to pay attention to than a fantasy draft prospect.

Anunoby is a strong 3-and-D player who has averaged 1.0 3PG despite playing only 20 MPG as a pro. With Kawhi Leonard gone, Anunoby has the opportunity to earn a significantly larger role for the Raptors that could make him worthy of a late-round flier in roto leagues.

Bertans was traded to the Wizards during the offseason, and he has the opportunity to compete for one of the starting forward slots. Even if he comes off the bench, he looks poised to have the biggest role of his career. Bertans averaged 1.9 3PG in only 21.5 MPG off the bench for the Spurs, and with increased minutes, he could be a strong 3-point role player in roto leagues.

Redick is coming off the best season of his 13-year career, averaging career bests of 18.1 PPG and 3.2 3PG in 31.3 MPG for the 76ers. This offseason, he moved to a Pelicans squad that could desperately use his shooting but has enough talent on the perimeter that he may not get the minutes to match last season's production. Still, he projects as a strong source of 3-pointers with double-figures scoring.

Reddish is considered one of the more talented rookies in this class, but he never quite put his total offensive package together at the collegiate level. He's got great size for a wing and the potential to be the best perimeter scorer in this class. He has some development to do, though, and with a relatively deep Hawks core on the wing, he may not produce fantasy-caliber numbers early in the season. He is worthy of either a late-round flier or a spot on your radar if he sits on the waiver wire.

Porzingis sat out the entirety of last season recovering from a spring 2017 torn ACL, and this season will make his debut as a member of the Dallas Mavericks. Porzingis, when healthy, is a legit 20-10 big-man threat with strong shot-blocking and 3-point shooting who would seemingly fit perfectly next to do-everything creator Luka Doncic. But health is such a huge question, so he might slide into the early-to-middle rounds of fantasy drafts despite having top-20 upside.

Harris struggled with injury last season, forcing him to miss 25 games and limiting his production all season. He did bounce back a bit during the playoffs, and this season, he has mid-teens scoring upside with plus 3-pointers on strong shooting percentages, which makes him a top-100 prospect with more value in roto than points leagues.

Poeltl may open the season as the starting center for the Spurs, a role in which he would have low double-double upside. Big men score well in points leagues, so as a starter he could be worth a late-round flier.

Curry seems poised to take to another level this season, with Kevin Durant out of town and Klay Thompson still recovering from ACL surgery. With newly acquired D'Angelo Russell on board to keep defenses from being able to play box-and-one on Curry the way the Raptors did in the Finals, Curry has legitimate 30 PPG potential with his characteristically monster 3-point shooting and excellent percentages.

Doncic turned in a Rookie of the Year season at age 19, having just moved to America, and he has the strong potential to improve across the board as a second-year player who is acclimated to the NBA and now has a team with some talent to lead. If Kristaps Porzingis is healthy and productive, Doncic has 20-point triple-double potential on a nightly basis and top-25 upside in both points and roto leagues.

Ayton was actually the top rookie producer in points-based leagues for much of the season when injuries weren't slowing him. He has easy 20-10 upside as a sophomore with strong shooting percentages and the potential to average both a block and a steal per game. With opposing defenses focused on Devin Booker and a true point guard in Ricky Rubio, Ayton could be in for a leap in Year 2.

Harrell turned in a career-best effort last season, setting personal bests with 16.6 PPG, 6.5 RPG, 2.0 APG and 1.3 BPG while shooting an outstanding 61.5 FG% in 26.3 MPG. Harrell projects to a similar role as the primary big man off the bench this season, and at 25, he still has the potential to improve. He is a top 75 fantasy draft prospect in roto leagues, and might be top 50 in points leagues.

Rozier has averaged 20.5 PP100, 8.7 RPG, 5.9 APG, 3.5 3P100 and 1.9 SP100 over 159 games in a sixth-man role with the Celtics for the past two seasons, and he showed flashes of what he could do with more time during the 2018 playoffs, during which he averaged 16.5 PPG, 5.5 APG, 5.3 RPG, 2.7 3PG and 1.3 SPG in 36.6 MPG during 19 games starting in place of Kyrie Irving. He'll step in as the immediate offensive engine on a depleted Hornets roster that needs to replace the combined 32.9 FGA/game of the departed Kemba Walker and Jeremy Lamb.

Williamson was the top overall pick this season and projects to numbers that could be worthy of the second round of fantasy drafts. He is too big for small forwards to guard and too quick for big men, and he could challenge for 20 and 10 with strong peripheral numbers as a rookie. Note, however, that he is expected to miss the beginning of the season due to a knee injury.

Whiteside was traded to the Trail Blazers this offseason, which could be a boon for his numbers after he fell out of the starting role with the Heat last season. Starting center Jusuf Nurkic is still recovering from the horrific leg injury that could cause him to miss at least the first half of this season, so Whiteside should have the chance to establish himself as a dominant rebounder and defender who can finish with high efficiency while playing off of the Trail Blazers' talented guards.

Gilgeous-Alexander had a great rookie season that had him pegged as the point guard of the future for the Clippers -- before the Thunder made him a sticking point in the Paul George trade. Gilgeous-Alexander still has upside for the Thunder, though he will be battling Chris Paul and Dennis Schroder for playing time at both guard spots. Gilgeous-Alexander could be the starter at shooting guard, moving off the ball and exchanging assist potential for more scoring and shooting to go with his solid defensive potential. He projects as a middle-round roto prospect due to that upside on a potentially rebuilding Thunder team.

Oubre came to the Suns from the Wizards midway through last season and immediately achieved career-best averages of 16.9 PPG, 45.3 FG%, 4.9 RPG, 1.7 3PG, 1.4 SPG and 1.0 BPG. He signed a big extension during the offseason and projects as the starting small forward in what should be a more powerful Suns offense led by a true point guard in Ricky Rubio. He projects to be in the top 50 in roto leagues and in that same vicinity in points leagues.

Fournier played in a career-best 81 games last season after losing a combined 39 games to injuries in the previous two seasons, but he also struggled with his shot, turning in his lowest field goal percentage as a member of the Magic and his lowest scoring average in four seasons. He did set new career bests in assists and rebounds, but typically he will get most of his value from scoring and long-range shooting. He projects as a mid-round prospect in roto drafts this season.

Rondo is back for Season 2 next to LeBron James with the Lakers, this time as the presumptive starter with Lonzo Ball off to New Orleans. Rondo is exactly who he is at this stage of his career, and the only questions are health (he hasn't topped 72 games played since 2009-10) and minutes played. The Lakers value Rondo's leadership, but his lack of shooting could cause him to give way to Kentavious Caldwell-Pope or Avery Bradley in the closing unit, which would cap his minutes and production just below starter levels.

Thompson averaged a low double-double last season, but he also played in only 43 games due to injury. The Cavaliers are a young, rebuilding team, so it is unclear how large of a role Thompson will have this season. With starter minutes, he'd project to average a double-double again, but his type of production doesn't translate well to fantasy when earning bench minutes.

Hunter is an NBA-ready combo forward, mature for a rookie, and has great size and strength to play the wing. He is a jack of all trades with good defensive upside and solid shooting potential. He could be a double-digit scorer with good enough all-around numbers as a rookie to be worth a late-round flier.

Ingles has carved out a useful role for the Jazz as a do-everything wing on modest overall volume, though he is also a high-volume 3-point producer. The Jazz brought in Mike Conley this offseason to set the table, which if anything might help Ingles to get even more open looks this season.

Embiid showed last season that he could play heavy minutes while maintaining his monster per-possession averages, but he also wore down physically late in the season, which is partially blamed for the 76ers not advancing further in the playoffs. As a result, the 76ers brought Al Horford to town, so Embiid might play fewer minutes with more maintenance rest games, but when he's on the court, he should still be a top-10 producer in both roto and points leagues.

Butler appears poised for his best statistical output since his days with the Bulls now that he is the primary threat on the Heat as opposed to playing secondary roles next to dominant offensive big men in his past two stops. Butler projects as one of the best scorers in the NBA who should contribute across the board on both offense and defense as "the man" for the Heat.

Tatum had a huge rookie season and was perceived to have stagnated a bit in Year 2, but per possession, he actually improved in scoring, rebound, assist and 3-point volume as a sophomore. His efficiency did take a step backward, but the theory is that with Kyrie Irving and Terry Rozier now on other teams, the Celtics will rely more upon their third-year rising star for a larger role that features him more.

Randle made the leap to a fantasy impact player last season, averaging 25.0 PPG on 49.6 FG% during his last 22 games as the primary option for the Pelicans. This season, he projects to build on that production with a talent-depleted Knicks squad that would support him scoring in the upper 20s and flirting with 10 rebounds and four assists per game. He is a top-20 prospect in both points and roto leagues this season.

McCollum has turned in four straight seasons of at least 21 PPG, 3.0 RPG, 3.0 APG and 2.3 3PG and should maintain or even improve those numbers this season as he enters his athletic peak. McCollum may also be asked to carry a heavier offensive load while Jusuf Nurkic recovers from injury, as Hassan Whiteside doesn't sport as large of an offensive footprint, which may push more shots to the backcourt.

Jackson had an impressive rookie season that led to a First Team All-Rookie selection despite playing only 58 games due to injury. He projects as the centerpiece for the rebuilding Grizzlies with upper-teens scoring upside and plus production in blocks, steals and 3-pointers that could lead him to top-50 value in roto leagues.

Adams had solidified his role as a high-efficiency finisher playing off of Russell Westbrook with strong rebounding and defense numbers, and he turned in his best numbers last season. The departures of Westbrook and Paul George could open up more offensive volume for Adams, and Chris Paul is excellent at running the pick-and-roll, so Adams' bread-and-butter play should remain a staple of the Thunder offense.

Schroder was solid as a backup to Russell Westbrook last season and has more upside this season with Chris Paul replacing Westbrook. Paul is older, plays fewer minutes and is a larger injury risk than Westbrook was, which could give Schroder more playing time and more usage this season.

Hayward struggled in his first season back after his horrific ankle injury in 2017, posting poor numbers with major inconsistencies in ability and role as the season went along. This season, he is a year further into the recovery process, and with the Celtics' offseason moves, he should have a larger role as well. He may not bounce all the way back to his Jazz-level production, but he should at least return to fantasy-starter caliber this season.

Rose had a big bounce-back campaign last season with the Timberwolves, averaging 18.0 PPG, 4.3 APG, 2.7 RPG and 1.1 3PG in 27.3 MPG in the 51 games he played. He parlayed that into a new contract with the Pistons and is expected to back up starter Reggie Jackson. He has the upside to challenge Jackson for the job if he can remain healthy -- but that's always a huge "if," for Rose.

Bogdanovic spent most of last season coming off the bench but still improved as a sophomore to 14.1 PPG, 3.8 APG, 3.5 RPG and 1.9 3PG. He should fulfill a similar role this season, though Trevor Ariza has also joined the team and could make minutes slightly harder to come by. Bogdanovic still has some upside as a third-year player and should be a solid scoring/3-point-shooting role player who goes in the middle-late rounds in roto leagues.

Kennard showed some signs of improvement in his second season, averaging 9.7 PPG in 22.8 MPG and, more importantly, knocking down 1.7 3PG on 39.4 3FG%. He could challenge for more consistent starter minutes this season and projects as a 3-point role-player prospect in roto leagues, though he is unlikely to draw attention in points leagues without a major leap in production.

DeRozan became a more well-rounded player last season when he joined the Spurs, turning in career highs of 6.2 APG and 6.0 RPG while shooting 48.1% from the field, his best percentage since his rookie season. He still averaged more than 20 PPG as well, though his scoring volume decreased on the more balanced Spurs. His lack of 3-point shooting hurts his roto value, but his all-around contributions still make him a top-40 prospect.

Gasol's numbers dropped dramatically after his trade to the Raptors last season, as his playing time dipped to 24.9 MPG and he was asked to fill a specific role. Similar to Jonas Valanciunas before him, this minutes limit puts a serious cap on his volume. The Raptors won a championship playing that style and, even with Kawhi Leonard gone, are unlikely to give Gasol anywhere near the usage or minutes that he used to enjoy with the Grizzlies.

Beal ramped up his volume in a big way last season after John Wall tore his Achilles tendon, averaging 28.0 PPG (47.8 FG%, 82.3 FT%), 6.2 APG, 5.3 RPG, 2.8 3PG and 1.9 SPG in 43 games between Dec. 28 and the end of March. Beal will be asked to carry a similar load this season, which gives him top-20 upside in both points and roto leagues.

Lillard has averaged at least 25 PPG, 5.9 APG and 2.9 3PG in four straight seasons. He is coming off a playoff run that landed him in the headlines, and he has spent the summer speaking against super teams while signing a super-max extension. He is right in his peak at 29 years old, and should have another elite season.

Young had a slow start to his rookie season, but if Rookie of the Year were a second-half award, he'd have taken it easily. He averaged 22.5 PPG, 8.5 APG and 4.5 RPG on 43.9% FG and 35.5% 3FG during his last 42 games of the season. With a season under his belt and an offseason to prepare on a young team that is unquestionably his but that has also added more young talent, Young seems poised to build upon that strong finish with a top-50 sophomore campaign.

LaVine broke out to post career-high numbers last season, averaging 23.7 PPG, 4.7 RPG, 4.5 APG, 1.9 3PG and 1.0 SPG in 34.5 MPG in 63 outings. He missed 19 games last season and has missed 102 games during the past three campaigns, making health a huge concern for him. However, he clearly is the best perimeter scorer on the rebuilding Bulls and has the upside to improve upon those numbers as he approaches his athletic peak at age 24.

Bagley had a very strong rookie season, and the Kings plan to feature him more this season after letting Willie Cauley-Stein leave. Bagley averaged a robust 18.6 PPG and 9.5 RPG during the last month of the season and has the upside to build on those numbers with a 3-pointer and a block per game this season.

Bryant burst onto the scene for the Wizards last season in Dwight Howard's absence, and he enters this season as the full-time starter at center. Bryant averaged 11.4 PPG, 7.1 RPG and 1.4 APG in 53 starts last season, and at only 22 years old he has the upside to develop across the board and produce impact numbers in his third season.  He is worthy of mid-to-late-round consideration in fantasy drafts.

Bogdanovic parlayed a career-best effort last season into a huge contract with the Jazz this offseason, and he fits in very well as a stretch-4 next to Rudy Gobert in the frontcourt. He should produce strong scoring, 3-point shooting and percentages, though he doesn't contribute much in traditional big-man categories like rebounds or blocks.

Gordon and Nikola Vucevic showed that they are still the frontcourt of the present in Orlando even after Mo Bamba and Jonathan Isaac were drafted as the frontcourt of the future. Gordon had the healthiest season of his career as a starter, starting 78 games and playing a career-best 33.8 MPG while producing solid scoring, rebounding, assists and 3-pointers. He is a top-75 prospect in points leagues this season.

Brown was the young Celtics wing who was most squeezed for role and minutes last season with the returns of Kyrie Irving and Gordon Hayward from injury, and his five-minute cut in playing time per game resulted in drops across the board in all of the counting categories despite his per-possession numbers remaining steady. However, with Irving, Terry Rozier and Marcus Morris out of town, Brown should have a larger role and get the chance to become a fantasy starter again this season.

Sexton had a sneaky-strong rookie season, averaging 21.1 PPG on 47.0% from the field and 41.7% from behind the arc with 3.3 APG, 2.6 RPG and 2.4 3PG during his last 29 games. He is the early focal point of the Cavaliers' rebuilding efforts, so he has upside to grow beyond his rookie hot streak, although he may have to battle players with similar skill sets (rookie Darius Garland and veteran Jordan Clarkson) for volume this season.

Hachimura looked very impressive during the NBA summer league, with the size, length, quickness and strength to play at either forward slot. Hachimura projects as a starting forward for the rebuilding Wizards, and he could be a plus scorer with solid defensive numbers, a handful of rebounds and even some 3-point production as a rookie. He is worth a late-round flier.

Morris had a strong season as the starting power forward for the Celtics, but during the offseason he joined a deep Knicks front line that could squeeze  his minutes. Morris has good scoring, 3-point shooting and rebounding production in starter minutes, but in a bench role his 3-point shooting could be the only thing that keeps him relevant in roto leagues.

Clarke was named the Most Outstanding Player during the NBA summer league in Las Vegas, which backed up the conference Rookie of the Year and Defensive Player of the Year awards that he won at Gonzaga last season. Clarke is an outstanding shot-blocker, a skill that could translate directly to the NBA, and he also has double-double potential when he gets playing time. He could get some run on a young Grizzlies team and is worthy of a late-round flier.

Bjelica had some strong numbers early in the season and, overall, had his best season as a pro but now finds himself battling for minutes off the bench, which makes it unlikely that he gets more than the 23.2 MPG he averaged last season. He has upside to score low double figures and grab a handful of rebounds per game, but his most interesting attribute is his shooting. He averaged 1.3 3PG from the power forward slot, which could get him some run as a roto role player in deep leagues.

Washington has good defensive potential, and even a bit of shooting upside, and most importantly he will be playing for a talent-strapped Hornets squad that is in full rebuild mode. Washington may not be worth drafting in most leagues, but he is definitely worth watching and scooping up at the first sign that he's earned a focal position for the Hornets.

Jokic burst onto the MVP scene last season as the most consistent triple-double threat this side of Russell Westbrook, and at 24 he should still be improving going into this season. He doesn't get quite enough assists to average a triple-double, but if he is in that neighborhood while averaging 20/10 and posting strong peripherals in every category including 3-pointers and shooting percentages. He's a legitimate top-5 draft pick with a weak but defendable case for No. 1.

Westbrook is joining James Harden with the Rockets for the chance to win a championship. As such, his days averaging anywhere near a triple-double are probably over. On the flip side, he struggled horribly from the field and free throw line last season. Fortunately, the Mike D'Antoni system is extremely friendly to point guards and could help get Westbrook's shot back on track.

George joined Kawhi Leonard in moving to the Clippers this offseason, a move that caps his upside as the second star on a team with a lot of peripheral talent. However, he has shown that he can ramp up his 3-point shooting and defensive numbers when not asked to carry as much scoring volume, and his unique category contributions will help him remain a top option in rotisserie leagues.

Lauri Markkanen has been one of the most impressive members of the 2017 draft class when healthy. Though the Bulls brought in veteran Thaddeus Young at his position in the offseason, Markkanen has the ability to become a franchise player with 20-10 points-rebounds potential a real possibility, in addition to his excellent volume shooting beyond the arc.

Harris understandably lost some scoring volume last season with his trade to the 76ers, but with Jimmy Butler gone, Harris could edge back up to 20 PPG this season as the clear second option behind Joel Embiid. He is also a strong contributor in rebounds and 3-point shooting. Harris starts the season with top-50 upside in both roto and points formats.

Ball was traded to the New Orleans Pelicans, where he projects as the starting point guard on a young team with a lot of talent. He should get to run the show full time, improving his assist potential dramatically compared to last season next to LeBron James. Ball has to show that he can remain healthy, but he has low triple-double potential every night with plus steals and 3-pointers, giving him top-50 upside this season.

Williams has been the primary scorer for the Clippers as a sixth man during the past two seasons, but with the additions of Kawhi Leonard and Paul George, he becomes the third option at best. This could cap his volume a bit, but he should still get run as the main option on the second unit, giving him plus potential as a scorer and 3-point shooter.

Turner continues to battle Domantas Sabonis for center minutes, and just when it looked as if Sabonis might move more to the power forward slot this season, the Pacers drafted highly regarded center Goga Bitadze in the first round this summer. Nevertheless, Turner has established himself as a nightly low double-double threat with league-leading shot-blocking capability and around a made 3-pointer and a steal per game. This combo makes him more valuable in roto than points-based leagues.

Ibaka proved very productive in his role off the bench last season, averaging 15.0 PPG, 8.1 RPG and 1.4 BPG in 27.2 MPG. While his days leading the NBA in blocked shots are over, Ibaka is a versatile producer who is still a borderline top-60 prospect in roto leagues with upside if his 3-point shot bounces back up to the 1.5 3PG that he averaged in his first two seasons with the Raptors.

Clarkson is coming off his best season as a pro, averaging 16.8 PPG, 3.3 RPG, 2.4 APG and 1.8 3PG in a sixth-man role. Clarkson is likely to reprise that role this season, though he might have to battle with second-year player Collin Sexton and rookie Darius Garland for shots in a three-man rotation of overlapping skill sets.

Dinwiddie has improved significantly in each of the previous three seasons, improving his scoring from 15.4 PP100 and 1.4 3P100 during the 2016-17 season up to 28.4 PP100 and 3.1 3P100 last season. He fluctuates between starting and sixth-man duties, and he seems likely to maintain that role again this season with his eight-figure salary dictating a large opportunity for the talented wing despite the other changes on the Nets' roster.

Smart is the kind of tough, defense-minded spark plug who has a larger impact in NBA basketball than he does in fantasy. However, those very attributes have carved out a large, consistent role for Smart as a borderline starter/sixth man. His play on Team USA should raise his profile and confidence this season, and he is always a strong source of steals with 3-pointers and assists as secondary categories of influence.

Gay has found a home with the Spurs, and last season averaged 13.7 PG, 6.8 RPG, 2.6 APG and 1.1 3PG while shooting 50.4 percent from the field and 81.6 percent from the line. He projects to a similar role this season, and those numbers are worthy of mid-to-late-round attention in roto leagues but only fringe draft status in points leagues.

Green joins the Lakers this season and will be playing the exact same 3-and-D role that he has mastered in previous stops with the Spurs and Raptors. His numbers for the Lakers should, therefore, look very similar to what he's produced during the past few seasons of his career.

Dunn was once the promising point guard of the future for the Bulls, but after two seasons of injury, the Bulls brought in Tomas Satoransky and spent a lottery pick on Coby White, which squeezes Dunn for minutes. He's in a put-up season for the Bulls, with health, shot selection and an increased ability to run the team the biggest areas that he needs to improve upon to earn a larger share of the pie.
